quizzes.question:
Style the first child of the <p> element.
[!raw!]
{0} : first-{1} {
   background-color: yellow;
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Working with Pseudo-Classes[/h1]

The CSS pseudo-classes allow us to style elements, or parts of elements, that exist in the document tree without using JavaScript or any other scripts. A pseudo-class starts with a "[b]:[/b]" (colon).
The most commonly used pseudo-classes are [b]:first-child[/b] and [b]:last-child[/b]. 

The [b]:first-child[/b] pseudo-class matches an element that is the first child element of some other element. 
In the following example, the selector matches any <p> element that is the first child of the div element:

[b]The HTML:[/b][code format="html" ]<div id="parent">
   <p>First paragraph</p>
   <p>Second paragraph</p>
   <p>Third paragraph</p>
   <p>Fourth paragraph</p>
</div>[/code]
[b]The CSS:[/b][code format="css" codeId="591"]#parent p:[b]first-child[/b] {
   color: green;
   text-decoration: underline;   
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2678" width="100%"]
The [b]:last-child[/b] pseudo-class matches an element that is the last child element of some other element. 

In the example below, the selector will match any <p> element that is the last child of the div element: [code format="css" codeId="592"]#parent p:[b]last-child[/b] {
   color: green;
   text-decoration: underline;   
}[/code]
[b]Result: [/b][img id="2679" width="100%"]
